[2]
Date: Sat 2 Mar 2007
From: Joseph Dudley <fnjpd@uaf.edu>
Source: Itar-Tass News Agency [edited]
<http://www.itar-tass.com/eng/level2.html?NewsID=11299320&PageNum=0>

HFRS Outbreak in Lipetsk Region predicted
-----------------------------------------------
Epidemiologists [predict] a new outbreak of hemorrhagic fever with
kidney syndrome (HFRS) in the Lipetsk Region this spring 2007,
regional chief epidemiologist Lyudmial Kirillov told ITAR-TASS on Fri
2 Mar 2007. She said that the outbreak was related to the awakening
of rodents that spread the disease.
By the beginning of March 2007, 244 human cases of this dangerous
disease have been registered in the Lipetsk region. 27 people,
including 3 children, have been hospitalized. Most of the HFRS cases,
176, occurred in the Dorinsky district.
Specialists are of the opinion that the HFRS outbreak in central
Russia was caused by the unusually warm winter. The causative virus
dies in 30-degree frost. The abundance of food on fields, which long
remained uncovered by the snow, also helped an increase in the rodent
population.
Tests have shown that every 3rd field mouse carries the virus, which
can be transmitted to humans via air. However, even affected humans
are not spreaders of infection.
The Lipetsk regional administration has allocated additional funds
for a rodent extermination program.
--
Joseph P. Dudley, Ph.D
Research Associate,
Institute of Arctic Biology
University of Alaska Fairbanks
<fnjpd@uaf.edu>
[Hemorrhagic fever with renal syndrome (HFRS) is a group of
clinically similar illnesses caused by hantaviruses of the family
_Bunyaviridae_. The viruses that cause HFRS include Hantaan,
Dobrava-Belgrade, Seoul, and Puumala. Puumala virus is likely to be
the virus causing HFRS in the Central Federal Region of Russia.
A picture of the reservoir rodent host (_Apodemus agrarius_) and
other information is available at
<http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/dvrd/spb/mnpages/dispages/hfrs.htm>.
ProMED-mail does not routinely report outbreaks of HFRS in endemic
regions of Russia and middle Asia, but recent benign weather
conditions may be exacerbating the disease situation.
A map of the Central Federal Region of the Russian Federation is
accessible at
<http://www.answers.com/topic/federal-districts-of-russia>. - Mod.CP]
